Accounting for dividends gains: stock portfolio real performance calculator¶

Motivation¶

A brokerage account normally allows to quickly check the unrealized capital gain/loss of the portfolio, that is, the money the investor would gain/lose if he sold his stocks at that moment. However, this value doesn't take into account the dividends a company has paid throughout the time the investor has held the stock. Specifically, the potential gain/loss doesn't account for the reinvested dividends or the dividends held in cash. The following simplified example further illustrates the problematic.

In [1]:
import os
#Go to image's location
path = "D:\Personal\Inversion"
os.chdir(path)

from IPython.display import Image
Image(filename='Div_explanation.png')
Out[1]:

Thus, the investor may think he has a 10% gain on his initial investment but, in reality, he has around 15% gain, accounting for dividends.

Or

The investor is aware that his real gain is not 10%, but does not have quick/easy access to his real gain/loss on an specific dividend stock or overall portfolio.

Final note: This simplified example does not account for Tax reduction on the gains. Then again, the unrealized capital gain shown in the brokerage account does not account for this reduction either. As Tax deduction depends on the personal situation of each investor, the following calculator will focus on gross profit.

Performance calculator¶

In this notebook, a tool for automatically calculating the real performance of a stock portfolio is developed. Specifically, this tool aims to account for both the capital gain/loss and the dividends the company has paid to the investor.

To do so, the following steps are done:

  • Data preparation: The csv files from the brokerage account are imported, and the data of each database is prepared for data analysis.
  • Data transformation: The different databases are used to account for dividend gains and compute the real gain/loss of each stock investment. The results are merged into a final database.
  • Data visualization: The real performance of stocks is visually compared to the gain/loss indicated by the brokerage account. The importance of accounting for dividends gain is reflected.

All of the steps were done with Python and its libraries.

Data exploration and transformation¶

In [2]:
#Import required libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Now let's import the csv databases of importance. In particular:

  • Positions file: Contains the current holdings of the portfolio.
  • Transactions file: Contains the history of the transactions made in the account.

These files should be readily available to download on the personal brokerage account of each investor. For this work, we'll use the files format provided by a Charles Schwab brokerage account, as they are one of the largest brokerage firms. Nevertheless, this tool is applicable to every brokerage firm, with minor adjustements.

Text mining¶

Much cleaner! Now, let's do some text mining and make sure we have numeric values in each column of interest, instead of strings.

In [7]:
#Replace "--" string with numpy nans, to be able to make operations on columns.
pos.replace('--',np.nan, inplace =True)
#Group columns into dollar and percentage values
Dolcol=['Price','Market Value','Cost Basis', 'Gain/Loss $']
Percol=['Gain/Loss %','% Of Account','Dividend Yield']
Numcol=['Quantity']
#Delete symbols and convert to numeric values
pos[Dolcol] = pos[Dolcol].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
pos[Percol] = pos[Percol].replace('[\$%,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
pos[Numcol] = pos[Numcol].astype(float)

In [11]:
#Let's remove the buy/sell actions
div = trans[~trans["Action"].isin(['Buy','Sell'])]

Quick nomenclature:

  • Cash dividend / Qual Div Reinvest / Qualified Dividend: Total Dividends payments received from the company, subject to Tax deduction.
  • NRA Tax Adj: Tax amount deducted from dividends payment.
  • Reinvest Shares: Dividend income (after tax deduction) reinvested in the company.

Let's put the cash position and account total into single variables, so we can drop those rows and have the final dataset

In [24]:
Holdings['Real Cost Basis']=(Holdings['Cost Basis']+Holdings['Reinvested']).round(2)
Holdings['Real Gain/Loss $']=(Holdings['Market Value']+ Holdings['Cash'] -Holdings['Div. tax deduction'] 
                              - Holdings['Real Cost Basis']).round(2)

#Holdings['Real Cost Basis'][7] = Holdings['Real Cost Basis'][0:6].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total', 'Real Cost Basis'] = Holdings['Real Cost Basis'][:-2].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total', 'Dividends'] = Holdings['Dividends'][:-2].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total', 'Div. tax deduction'] = Holdings['Div. tax deduction'][:-2].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total', 'Reinvested'] = Holdings['Reinvested'][:-2].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total', 'Cash'] = Holdings['Cash'][:-2].sum()
Holdings.loc[Holdings.Symbol=='Account Total','Real Gain/Loss $'] = Holdings['Real Gain/Loss $'][:-2].sum()

Holdings['Real Gain/Loss %']=(Holdings['Real Gain/Loss $']*100/Holdings['Real Cost Basis']).round(2)

Computing the change¶

Let's give a more suitable name to some columns and then add two columns to obtain the final dataframe:

  • Percentage points change: Reflects the absolute percentage points change between the recently computed real gain (accounting for dividends), and the apparent Gain/Loss reflected on the brokerage account.
  • Relative change in gain: Reflects the relative change in gains when accounting for dividends. With this metric, we are taking into account the "sizes" of the values being compared.
In [25]:
newname = {'Cost Basis': 'Apparent Cost Basis',
           'Gain/Loss $': 'Apparent Gain/Loss $',
           'Gain/Loss %': 'Apparent Gain/Loss %'}
Holdings.rename(columns=newname, inplace=True)
Holdings['Percentage Points change [-]'] = (Holdings['Real Gain/Loss %'] - Holdings['Apparent Gain/Loss %']).round(2)
Holdings['Relative change in gain %'] = ((Holdings['Real Gain/Loss %'] - 
                                          Holdings['Apparent Gain/Loss %'])*100/Holdings['Apparent Gain/Loss %']).round(2)

Comparing these stocks, we can see that the absolute percentage point change is roughly similar (3.7 vs 4.8 points). Nevertheless, the relative change have a dramatic increase for AT&T, and the reasoning behind it is the key motivation of this project:

  • CVS stock price has performed well, going up 23.3% since its initial buy (capital gain). On the other hand, the dividend yield is at around 2.7%, which is not bad, but it is not considered a high dividend yield. Consequently, the capital gains are larger than the dividends payments received for this stock. Nevertheless, accounting for dividends results in a relative increase of 16% of gains (3.7/27.0), which is considerable.
  • Respecting AT&T, the main source of gains comes from the dividends payments, with a dividend yield near 7%. Moreover, the stock price has not move much. Then, the opposite phenomena occurs: the dividend income is much larger than the capital gains. Then, accounting only for capital gain (as in the brokerage account) would not show not even a close performance of the stock. This is why including dividends gains results in a relative increase of 207.8% (4.8/2.3) !!
  • Therefore, this computation is more and more important as the influence of dividend income on the stock performance increases.
